                  </persName>
            . I am shopman to Peter Pige, a <rs id="t18320216-244-viclabel1386" type="occupation">pawnbroker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320216-244-victim2038 t18320216-244-viclabel1386"></join>, of <placeName id="t18320216-244-crimeloc1387">Church-street, Bethnal-green</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320216-244-crimeloc1387" type="placeName" value="Church-street, Bethnal-green"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320216-244-crimeloc1387" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320216-244-off1384 t18320216-244-crimeloc1387"></join>. On the morning of the 21st of January, I saw the prisoner close to the window - I afterwards saw him running; I went out, stopped him, and took him back to the shop, and found on him these eight silk handkerchiefs, which are my master's.</p>
               <p>PETER PIGE. I had seen these handkerchiefs safe about ten minutes before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Where had they been hanging? A. Over the iron bar outside the window - they were tied by a string; a little girl told me you snatched them off - I pursued, and saw you trying to tuck them under your jacket, as you were running.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The handkerchiefs were laying under the shop-window; she kicked them with her foot - my wife died three days after I was put in prison, and left four children; I was discharged from the chilvers brig in September.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320216-244-person2040">
                  EDWARD 
                  DARKIN
               <interp inst="t18320216-244-person2040" type="surname" value="DARKIN"></interp>
